7.0 Bridging the Gap: Integrating Tokens with Development

To complete the design-to-development pipeline, design tokens must be synchronized with a central repository. This practice facilitates seamless collaboration between designers and developers, enables robust version control, and establishes a single source of truth for all design decisions.

7.1 Version Control and Syncing with GitHub

Tokens Studio supports multiple sync providers, including Local Storage, URL, JSONBin.io, GitLab, and Azure DevOps. However, GitHub is the recommended method because it hosts design decisions and code in the same location, is version-controlled, and allows for advanced automation through GitHub Actions.

Here is a step-by-step guide to syncing Tokens Studio with a GitHub repository:

1. Sign Up and Create a Repository in GitHub
  * Create a GitHub account if you don't have one.
  * Create a new repository and ensure you initialize it with a README file.
2. Generate a Personal Access Token
  * In GitHub, navigate to Settings > Developer Settings > Personal access tokens > Tokens (classic).
  * Click "Generate new token (classic)".
  * Give the token a descriptive note, set the expiration to "No Expiration," and check the "repo" scope.
  * Click "Generate token" and copy it immediately.
  * Security Warning: Store your access token securely, as you would a password. You will not be able to view it again. If it is ever exposed, revoke it immediately.
3. Configure Tokens Studio for Figma
  * Open your Figma project and launch the Tokens Studio plugin.
  * Go to the "Settings" tab.
  * Click "Add new" under Sync providers and select "GitHub."
4. Set Up GitHub as a Sync Provider
  * In the credentials modal, fill in the following fields:
    * Name: A descriptive name for the connection (e.g., CNHI DLS Github repo connect).
    * Personal Access Token: Paste the token you generated.
    * Repository: Your repository path (e.g., owner/repo).
    * Branch: The branch you want to sync with (e.g., figma-design-tokens).
    * File Path: The path to your JSON file (e.g., /tokens/figma/tokens.json).
  * Click "Save."
5. Sync Changes Between Figma and GitHub
  * You can now pull the latest changes from the repository or push your local changes.
  * To push, click the upload icon at the bottom of the plugin, enter a commit message describing your changes, and click "Push changes."
6. Create a Pull Request
  * After pushing, Tokens Studio will prompt you to "Create Pull Request."
  * This will redirect you to GitHub, where you can open a pull request to notify developers of the changes, allowing them to review and merge them into the main codebase.

